[2026-07-05] Task 4B - FULLY CLOSED (post-adversarial-fix, 3 rounds)
Adversarial review found two SIGNIFICANT real bugs: (1) no double-
submit guard, meaning a rapid double-click on Save could fire two
concurrent pushes and create genuine duplicate items in a user's real
Zotero library; (2) no guard preventing Disconnect/Cancel from racing
an in-flight push, meaning a stale push could complete and write items
AFTER the UI told the user they'd disconnected. Fixed with a
synchronous ref guard (the specialist's own first attempt using
React-Query's isPending state was itself broken - proven with a
failing test first, same class of bug as 2D's earlier re-entrancy fix)
and a confirmDisconnectDuringPush flow. Tester found one more gap
after that first fix: the disconnect-race guard was correctly wired
but had zero end-to-end test coverage (removing it entirely left all
tests green). Closed with 3 new tests driving a genuinely in-flight
push through the real mounted UI. Every fix in this chain was
independently reproduced by tester before being accepted. Final:
213/213 backend, 159/159 frontend, 8/8 Playwright.

[2026-07-05] Task 4A - FULLY CLOSED (post-blocking-fix, adversarial
re-confirmed independently)
Adversarial review found a real BLOCKING issue: App.tsx's decide()
(the Sec11.4 single decision function) never called usePlaybackEngine's
real cancel() - only wrote to a Zustand store - so mid-narration
decisions left the old paper's utterance speaking uninterrupted,
violating Sec6.6's explicit synchronous-cancel requirement and risking
cross-paper audio overlap or a stale callback auto-deciding a paper
the user never heard. Also found a SIGNIFICANT issue: useSwipeToDecide's
own re-entrancy guard was built but never wired up, so rapid double-
decisions could fire twice for the same paper. Both fixed: cancel()
now called synchronously as decide()'s first statement (generation-
based guard confirmed to correctly no-op any stale callback regardless
of the native Web Speech API's own cancel() timing); a synchronous
hasDecidedRef guard now genuinely blocks same-tick double-fires,
wired through StackScreen's new isDecisionPending prop.
Both fixes were verified twice: once by tester (who scrutinized 3
rewritten tests specifically for being a convenient rationalization
rather than a legitimate fix, concluding legitimate), and once more by
the SAME adversarial reviewer who found the original bugs, independently
re-attempting the original attacks against the fixed code rather than
trusting either report. One cosmetic-only finding survived (a
misleadingly-named test whose assertion is actually correct) - not
worth another round-trip, noted as a trivial backlog item.
Tier 4 (Tasks 4A, 4B, 4C) is now FULLY CLOSED. This tier alone
surfaced 5 real bugs across its three tasks (App.tsx error/offline
wiring gap, missing speechSynthesis.cancel(), a dead re-entrancy guard,
duplicate-push double-submit, and a disconnect/push race) - every one
caught by tester or adversarial-generalist, none by the specialist's
own testing, reinforcing why this project's checkpoint discipline is
non-negotiable even for "just wiring" tasks.

[2026-07-05] INCIDENT: frontend/src/App.tsx wiped to Tier 0 placeholder
Discovered during final Tier 4 sanity check: App.tsx matched commit
9749c74 (the very first commit) byte-for-byte, with zero git diff,
wiping out all of 4A/4B/4C's real wiring. Root cause: App.tsx was never
committed mid-session, so it had no local git history — a `git
checkout`-style step inside one of this session's many "temporarily
revert this change, confirm the test fails, then restore" verification
experiments (a pattern used throughout this build and explicitly
encouraged by this orchestrator) reset the file to HEAD's oldest
committed version instead of undoing the local edit, since there was
no intermediate commit to restore to. Recovered by asking the last
agent with verified-correct content to reconstruct App.tsx from its own
session context; re-verified independently (159/159 vitest, 8/8
Playwright, clean build) before committing.
PROCESS FIX going forward: commit each task's work to git as soon as
it's independently verified (tester + adversarial both cleared, no
BLOCKING findings open) — not batched until an entire tier closes.
This session's Tier 4 batching (holding 3 tasks' worth of work
uncommitted while multiple agents ran destructive revert/restore
verification cycles on shared files) is exactly the condition that let
this incident happen. All of Tier 4 is now committed (main@1dd8816).
